   "source": [
    "# CIFAR-10: ANN vs CNN\n",
    "\n",
    "Quick comparison of a plain fully-connected network against a few CNN variants\n",
    "on CIFAR-10. The goal is mostly to see *how much* the architecture matters once\n",
    "you're working with real images, not just to chase the highest possible number.\n",
    "\n",
    "Plan:\n",
    "1. Load and look at the data\n",
    "2. Train a basic ANN and a basic CNN, compare them\n",
    "3. Try a handful of small changes one at a time (deeper ANN, wider CNN, longer\n",
    "   training, early stopping, augmentation) and see what actually moves the\n",
    "   needle\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "3f8cb1fa",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import tensorflow as tf\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras import layers, models\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"TF:\", tf.__version__)\n",
    "print(\"GPU:\", tf.config.list_physical_devices('GPU'))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aae604a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data\n",
    "\n",
    "CIFAR-10 is 60k tiny 32x32 color images split into 10 classes, 50k for\n",
    "training and 10k held out for testing. `keras.datasets` ships it already\n",
    "split, which saves the trouble of dealing with the raw batches."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "850766ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = tf.keras.datasets.cifar10.load_data()\n",
    "\n",
    "class_names = ['airplane', 'automobile', 'bird', 'cat', 'deer',\n",
    "               'dog', 'frog', 'horse', 'ship', 'truck']\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"train:\", x_train.shape, \"test:\", x_test.shape)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "1b87b915",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# sanity check - make sure labels line up with what we expect to see\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 5, figsize=(10, 5))\n",
    "for ax, img, label in zip(axes.flat, x_train, y_train):\n",
    "    ax.imshow(img)\n",
    "    ax.set_title(class_names[label[0]])\n",
    "    ax.axis(\"off\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea9187aa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Preprocessing\n",
    "\n",
    "Two things need to happen before any of this goes into a model:\n",
    "\n",
    "- scale pixels from 0-255 down to 0-1 (training is a lot more stable this way)\n",
    "- the ANN can't take a 32x32x3 tensor directly, so it gets a flattened copy\n",
    "  too. The CNN keeps the original 3D shape since that's the whole point of\n",
    "  using convolutions in the first place."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "92c971b4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x_train_norm = x_train / 255.0\n",
    "x_test_norm = x_test / 255.0\n",
    "\n",
    "x_train_flat = x_train_norm.reshape(len(x_train_norm), -1)\n",
    "x_test_flat = x_test_norm.reshape(len(x_test_norm), -1)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"flat:\", x_train_flat.shape, \" image:\", x_train_norm.shape)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bf10e69b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Reusable model builders\n",
    "\n",
    "Every model below is some variation of \"stack of dense layers\" or \"stack of\n",
    "conv blocks\", and I kept rewriting the same Sequential boilerplate with one\n",
    "number changed. Wrapping that in two small functions makes the rest of the\n",
    "notebook a lot shorter and means a typo in one CNN doesn't have to be fixed in\n",
    "four different places.\n",
    "\n",
    "- `build_ann` takes a list of hidden layer sizes and a matching list of\n",
    "  dropout rates (use `0` for \"no dropout after this layer\").\n",
    "- `build_cnn` takes a list of filter counts for the conv blocks. `padding`\n",
    "  and `bn_on_last` exist because two of the variants below use `'same'`\n",
    "  padding and batch-norm on the final conv block, while the others don't.\n",
    "- `fit_model` just wraps `.compile()` + `.fit()` with the settings every run\n",
    "  in this notebook shares (adam, batch size 64, 10% validation split)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "397d9fcb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def build_ann(hidden_sizes, dropout_rates, input_dim=3072, num_classes=10):\n",
    "    assert len(hidden_sizes) == len(dropout_rates)\n",
    "    net = models.Sequential()\n",
    "    net.add(layers.Dense(hidden_sizes[0], activation='relu', input_shape=(input_dim,)))\n",
    "    if dropout_rates[0] > 0:\n",
    "        net.add(layers.Dropout(dropout_rates[0]))\n",
    "    for size, drop in zip(hidden_sizes[1:], dropout_rates[1:]):\n",
    "        net.add(layers.Dense(size, activation='relu'))\n",
    "        if drop > 0:\n",
    "            net.add(layers.Dropout(drop))\n",
    "    net.add(layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))\n",
    "    return net\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def build_cnn(filters, padding='valid', bn_on_last=False, dense_units=128,\n",
    "              dropout=0.4, input_shape=(32, 32, 3), num_classes=10):\n",
    "    net = models.Sequential()\n",
    "    for i, f in enumerate(filters):\n",
    "        is_last = (i == len(filters) - 1)\n",
    "        if i == 0:\n",
    "            net.add(layers.Conv2D(f, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding=padding,\n",
    "                                   input_shape=input_shape))\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            net.add(layers.Conv2D(f, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding=padding))\n",
    "        if (not is_last) or bn_on_last:\n",
    "            net.add(layers.BatchNormalization())\n",
    "        if not is_last:\n",
    "            net.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))\n",
    "    net.add(layers.Flatten())\n",
    "    net.add(layers.Dense(dense_units, activation='relu'))\n",
    "    net.add(layers.Dropout(dropout))\n",
    "    net.add(layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))\n",
    "    return net\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def fit_model(model, x, y, epochs=10, callbacks=None, verbose=1):\n",
    "    model.compile(optimizer='adam',\n",
    "                  loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',\n",
    "                  metrics=['accuracy'])\n",
    "    return model.fit(x, y, epochs=epochs, batch_size=64,\n",
    "                      validation_split=0.1, callbacks=callbacks, verbose=verbose)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0f071bca",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Baseline ANN\n",
    "\n",
    "512 -> 256 -> 10, with dropout after the first layer. This treats every image\n",
    "as a flat list of 3072 numbers, so it has no idea that nearby pixels are\n",
    "related - it's just here as a reference point for how much that matters."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "8c6a7006",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ann_model = build_ann([512, 256], [0.3, 0])\n",
    "ann_model.summary()\n",
    "\n",
    "ann_history = fit_model(ann_model, x_train_flat, y_train, epochs=10)\n",
    "ann_test_loss, ann_test_acc = ann_model.evaluate(x_test_flat, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"ANN test accuracy:\", ann_test_acc)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d22a72e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Baseline CNN\n",
    "\n",
    "Three conv blocks (32 -> 64 -> 128 filters), batch-norm + max pooling after\n",
    "the first two, then a dense head. Same training budget as the ANN (10 epochs,\n",
    "batch size 64) so the comparison is fair."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "7152904e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cnn_model = build_cnn([32, 64, 128])\n",
    "cnn_model.summary()\n",
    "\n",
    "cnn_history = fit_model(cnn_model, x_train_norm, y_train, epochs=10)\n",
    "cnn_test_loss, cnn_test_acc = cnn_model.evaluate(x_test_norm, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"CNN test accuracy:\", cnn_test_acc)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "beff8114",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n",
    "plt.plot(ann_history.history['val_accuracy'], marker='o', label='ANN')\n",
    "plt.plot(cnn_history.history['val_accuracy'], marker='s', label='CNN')\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Epoch\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Validation accuracy\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"ANN vs CNN, 10 epochs each\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(alpha=0.3)\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "31089806",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Side-by-side numbers for the two baselines:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "4edf735f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "comparison = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    \"Model\": [\"ANN\", \"CNN\"],\n",
    "    \"Test Accuracy\": [ann_test_acc, cnn_test_acc],\n",
    "    \"Test Loss\": [ann_test_loss, cnn_test_loss],\n",
    "})\n",
    "comparison\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ee8cf21a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Variant 1 - deeper ANN\n",
    "\n",
    "Same idea as the baseline ANN but with four hidden layers instead of two\n",
    "(1024 -> 512 -> 256 -> 128), dropout shrinking as the layers get narrower.\n",
    "The point here is to see whether just adding depth helps a model that's\n",
    "still working on flattened pixels with no spatial structure."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "138e14af",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ann_deep_model = build_ann([1024, 512, 256, 128], [0.3, 0.3, 0.2, 0])\n",
    "ann_deep_model.summary()\n",
    "\n",
    "ann_deep_history = fit_model(ann_deep_model, x_train_flat, y_train, epochs=10)\n",
    "ann_deep_test_loss, ann_deep_test_acc = ann_deep_model.evaluate(x_test_flat, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"Deep ANN test accuracy:\", ann_deep_test_acc)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "798a27e1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Deepening the ANN tends to give a small bump at best, and it's not even\n",
    "guaranteed - the model is still blind to where pixels sit relative to each\n",
    "other, so more layers mostly just means more parameters to overfit with."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e99e836",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Variant 2 - wider CNN (4 conv blocks)\n",
    "\n",
    "Pushing the baseline CNN one block further: 32 -> 64 -> 128 -> 256 filters,\n",
    "`'same'` padding throughout, and batch-norm on the last block too (the\n",
    "baseline skips that). Checking whether the extra capacity is worth the extra\n",
    "compute."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "1961ae8c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cnn_scaled_model = build_cnn([32, 64, 128, 256], padding='same', bn_on_last=True)\n",
    "cnn_scaled_model.summary()\n",
    "\n",
    "cnn_scaled_history = fit_model(cnn_scaled_model, x_train_norm, y_train, epochs=10)\n",
    "cnn_scaled_test_loss, cnn_scaled_test_acc = cnn_scaled_model.evaluate(x_test_norm, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"Scaled CNN test accuracy:\", cnn_scaled_test_acc)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "29082123",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Variant 3 - same CNN, double the epochs\n",
    "\n",
    "Going back to the original 3-block CNN architecture, just training it for 20\n",
    "epochs instead of 10 to see whether validation accuracy keeps climbing or\n",
    "flattens out."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "47b60086",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cnn_20ep_model = build_cnn([32, 64, 128])\n",
    "cnn_20ep_history = fit_model(cnn_20ep_model, x_train_norm, y_train, epochs=20)\n",
    "cnn_20ep_test_loss, cnn_20ep_test_acc = cnn_20ep_model.evaluate(x_test_norm, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"CNN (20 epochs) test accuracy:\", cnn_20ep_test_acc)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "7ee9036d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n",
    "plt.plot(cnn_history.history['val_accuracy'], marker='s', label='10 epochs')\n",
    "plt.plot(cnn_20ep_history.history['val_accuracy'], marker='^', label='20 epochs')\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Epoch\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Validation accuracy\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Does training longer keep helping?\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(alpha=0.3)\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9dd6b303",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Variant 4 - early stopping\n",
    "\n",
    "Same architecture again, up to 20 epochs available, but with `EarlyStopping`\n",
    "watching validation loss (patience of 3, restores the best weights once it\n",
    "stops). The idea is to let training cut itself off instead of guessing the\n",
    "right number of epochs ahead of time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "d28982a2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3,\n",
    "                           restore_best_weights=True, verbose=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "cnn_es_model = build_cnn([32, 64, 128])\n",
    "cnn_es_history = fit_model(cnn_es_model, x_train_norm, y_train, epochs=20,\n",
    "                            callbacks=[early_stop])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Stopped after {len(cnn_es_history.history['loss'])} epochs (cap was 20)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "cnn_es_test_loss, cnn_es_test_acc = cnn_es_model.evaluate(x_test_norm, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"CNN + early stopping test accuracy:\", cnn_es_test_acc)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7f7d0f99",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Variant 5 - data augmentation\n",
    "\n",
    "Last change: a smaller 2-block CNN with random flips/rotation/zoom applied\n",
    "on the fly during training. Augmentation acts like a cheap regularizer -\n",
    "the model never sees the exact same image twice, so it has a harder time\n",
    "memorizing the training set. Trained with the same early-stopping setup as\n",
    "the previous variant so the comparison isn't muddied by epoch count."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "bfcf3078",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([\n",
    "    layers.RandomFlip(\"horizontal\"),\n",
    "    layers.RandomRotation(0.1),\n",
    "    layers.RandomZoom(0.1),\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "aug_cnn_model = models.Sequential([\n",
    "    data_augmentation,\n",
    "    layers.Conv2D(32, 3, activation='relu', input_shape=(32, 32, 3)),\n",
    "    layers.MaxPooling2D(),\n",
    "    layers.Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu'),\n",
    "    layers.MaxPooling2D(),\n",
    "    layers.Flatten(),\n",
    "    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),\n",
    "    layers.Dropout(0.4),\n",
    "    layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'),\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "early_stop_aug = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3,\n",
    "                                restore_best_weights=True, verbose=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "aug_history = fit_model(aug_cnn_model, x_train_norm, y_train, epochs=20,\n",
    "                         callbacks=[early_stop_aug])\n",
    "\n",
    "aug_test_loss, aug_test_acc = aug_cnn_model.evaluate(x_test_norm, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"Augmented CNN test accuracy:\", aug_test_acc)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "0ceb4f70",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n",
    "plt.plot(cnn_es_history.history['val_accuracy'], marker='s', label='no augmentation')\n",
    "plt.plot(aug_history.history['val_accuracy'], marker='o', label='with augmentation')\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Epoch\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Validation accuracy\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Does augmentation actually help here?\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(alpha=0.3)\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "186ddc16",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## All variants, side by side"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "45d2e249",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "final_comparison = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    \"Model\": [\n",
    "        \"ANN (baseline, 10ep)\",\n",
    "        \"CNN (baseline, 10ep)\",\n",
    "        \"ANN (4 layers, 10ep)\",\n",
    "        \"CNN (4 blocks, 32-256, 10ep)\",\n",
    "        \"CNN (baseline arch, 20ep)\",\n",
    "        \"CNN + early stopping (<=20ep)\",\n",
    "        \"CNN + augmentation + early stopping (<=20ep)\",\n",
    "    ],\n",
    "    \"Test Accuracy\": [\n",
    "        ann_test_acc, cnn_test_acc, ann_deep_test_acc, cnn_scaled_test_acc,\n",
    "        cnn_20ep_test_acc, cnn_es_test_acc, aug_test_acc,\n",
    "    ],\n",
    "    \"Test Loss\": [\n",
    "        ann_test_loss, cnn_test_loss, ann_deep_test_loss, cnn_scaled_test_loss,\n",
    "        cnn_20ep_test_loss, cnn_es_test_loss, aug_test_loss,\n",
    "    ],\n",
    "}).sort_values(\"Test Accuracy\", ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "final_comparison\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "78047fef",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))\n",
    "plt.barh(final_comparison[\"Model\"], final_comparison[\"Test Accuracy\"], color='steelblue')\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Test accuracy\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"All variants, ranked\")\n",
    "plt.gca().invert_yaxis()\n",
    "for i, v in enumerate(final_comparison[\"Test Accuracy\"]):\n",
    "    plt.text(v + 0.005, i, f\"{v:.3f}\", va='center')\n",
