   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0199aaa9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "- The CNN beats the ANN by a wide margin from the very first run, which\n",
    "  makes sense - convolutions actually exploit the fact that nearby pixels\n",
    "  are related, while the ANN just sees 3072 unordered numbers.\n",
    "- Making the ANN deeper barely moves the needle. More parameters doesn't\n",
    "  fix the underlying problem, which is that it has no concept of spatial\n",
    "  structure to begin with.\n",
    "- Adding a fourth, wider conv block gives the CNN a bit more headroom, at\n",
    "  the cost of a noticeably longer training time - worth it only if that\n",
    "  last bit of accuracy actually matters for the use case.\n",
    "- Training the same CNN for twice as long helps some, but the gains get\n",
    "  smaller each epoch - a sign that it's approaching what this particular\n",
    "  architecture can do on this data.\n",
    "- Early stopping doesn't necessarily push accuracy higher, but it avoids\n",
    "  babysitting the epoch count and protects against wasting time training\n",
    "  past the point of improvement.\n",
    "- Augmentation is the one change that meaningfully improves generalization\n",
    "  on a small, simple CNN - feeding it slightly different images every pass\n",
    "  makes it harder to just memorize the training set.\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, architecture (ANN vs CNN) matters far more than any of the\n",
    "individual tweaks tried afterward. Once you're using a CNN, augmentation and\n",
    "training schedule are the next things worth tuning."
   ]
  }
